body:
I'm raising this for discussion at this point, but I would like to propose a
simplification to the Ast modeling of loops. We already don't have `AstFor`,
and we very quickly get rid of `AstDoWhile`, so `AstWhile` is the only one in
most places. However `AstWhile` still has the issue of having an ambiguous
place to insert new statements created when lowering the loop condition (they
need to go both before loop entry and on the loop back edge).

As an alternative, one could model all source level loops without his having
this problem using the following 2 constructs:

```
AstLoop
  astgen op1p := stmtsp : List[NodeStmt]
  astgen op2p := contsp : List[NodeStmt]

AstBreak:
  astgen op1p := unlessp : AstNodeExpr
```

That is, an infinite loop with 2 sections, which executes as:
```
  while (ture) {
     stmtsp;
     // <- 'continue' inside 'stmtsp' goes here
     contsp;
  }
```

Plus a conditional 'break' statement, which branches after the loop if the
condition is false. (Or if you prefer we can call it AstLoopTest.)

The nice thing about this is that there is no issue of where to insert new
statements created for the condition (they go before the AstBreak), and you
still know if a condition is a loop condition (as opposed to an 'if' condition)
for error messages and the like. (AstBreak can be lowered to an
AstIf(AstJumpLabel) if you don't mind loosing the information that this was a
loop test)

Modeling the source level loops is pretty straight forward:


```
  while (cond) { body; }
  // Becomes
  loop {
    stmtps:
      break cond;
      body;
    contsp:
      <empty>
  }

  do { body; } while (cond);
  // Becomes
  loop {
    stmtps:
      body;
      break cond;
    contsp:
      <empty>
  }

  for (init; cond; step) { body; }
  // Becomes
  init
  loop {
    stmtps:
      break cond;
      body;
    contsp:
      step;
  }

  forever { body; }
  // Becomes
  loop {
    stmtps:
      body;
    contsp:
      <empty>
  }
```

Again the point here is to simplify the representation so we can always just go
"insert before" or "insert after" on a statement while lowering expressions.

It also has the nice side effect of not forcing the unrolling of the first
iteration of a 'do' loop, and because every loop is represented the same way,
we only need to have one algorithm for handling everything.

When emitting to C++, we can special case some configurations if needed to emit
more "readable" code, but GCC/Clang should not care and should be happy with
gotos and have no observable performance difference

